description.narrative:
1.1.1 The NDC creates a 14th working group on NDS/SDG financing;
1.1.2 The Development Finance Platform (DFP) is fully operational under the NDC;
1.2.1 A mechanism in place to systematically collect and analyze data/inputs from national and international stakeholders on SDG financing;
1.4.1 The national dialogue on alternative and innovative SDG financing options is effective and participatory;
1.4.2 Estimated inflow of off-budget financial resources for NDS and SDG targets is increased;
1.4.3 Relevant technical and managerial staff in partner institutions are trained on policy-based budgeting, gender responsive budgeting, SDG financing, and other;
1.5.1 The strength of Parliamentary oversight of SDG financing is enhanced through training;
1.5.2 Staff in the Parliamentary Economy and Finance Committee (PEFC) are trained on principles of gender responsive budgeting in the context of SDG financing;
1.5.3 Primary and secondary legislation is reviewed to ensure Parliamentary access to high-quality evidence and information on SDG financing;
2.2.3 A mechanism (i.e. tool) for monitoring and reporting of on-budget public expenditure (vis-à-vis SDGs) is in place.

comment.narrative:
1.1.1 -  None of the 13 working groups in the NDC are focusing on NDS/SDG financing;
1.1.2. - High-level Development Finance Platform (DFP) does not exist;
1.2.1. - No mechanism in place to systematically collect and analyze data/inputs on SDG financing;
1.4.1. - The national dialogue on SDG financing is weak and disjointed;
1.4.2. - Financing to achieve the national SDG targets covers only 6.7% of the gap
1.4.3. - Targeted training of relevant staff at technical and management level is largely ad hoc and uncoordinated;
1.5.1. - Parliamentary oversight of SDG financing is nonexistent;
1.5.2. - Gender responsive budgeting does not exist in Tajikistan; 
1.5.3. - Parliament does not request (or have access to) evidence or information on SDG financing;
2.2.3. - No mechanism or tool in place

1.1.1. - 14th working group in the NDC is created, focusing on NDS/SDG financing matters;
1.1.2. - Government endorses the creation of a high-level DFP under the NDC;
1.2.1. - Inputs from stakeholders are systematized and analyzed by the DFP/NDC Working Group;
1.4.1. - At least 2 coordination meetings are held within DFP / NDC, using evidence generated by the programme;
1.4.2. - NONE; 
1.4.3. - At least 100 staff at technical level and 40 staff at managerial level, including 40% women, are trained;
1.5.1. - 100% of staff, including women in the Parliamentary committees complete at least 3 professional training courses on budgeting, planning and SDGs;
1.5.2. - 100% of staff, including women, in the PEFC are trained;
1.5.3. - A summary report is prepared with key findings from the review of primary and secondary legislation;
2.2.3. - Concept for monitoring and reporting of SDG financing is endorsed by the government.

1.1.1. - postponed to 2021 due to GoT decision to change the main partner of the project from Ministry of Finance to Ministry of Economic Development and Trade. In 2020, national expertise engaged to initiate the assessment of the Finance Architecture in the country. An action plan along with the methodology and approach to stakeholder engagement and data gathering finalized. 
1.1.2. - postponed to 2021 due to GoT decision to change the main partner of the project from Ministry of Finance to Ministry of Economic Development and Trade;
1.2.1. - postponed due to COVID-19;
1.4.1. - postponed due to COVID-19;
1.4.2. - NONE; 
1.4.3. - postponed due to COVID-19;
1.5.1. - postponed due to COVID-19;
1.5.2. - postponed due to COVID-19;
1.5.3. - postponed due to COVID-19;
2.2.3. - postponed due to COVID-19.
